            "title": "Chapter 7. Mechanism Design for the Environment",
            "abstract": "We argue that when externalities such as pollution are nonexcludable, agents must be compelled to participate in a \u201cmechanism\u201d to ensure a Pareto-efficient outcome. We survey some of the main findings of the mechanism-design (implementation-theory) literature \u2013 such as the Nash implementation theorem, the Gibbard\u2013Satterthwaite theorem, the Vickrey\u2013Clarke\u2013Groves mechanism, and the Arrow/d\u2019Aspremont\u2013Gerard\u2013Varet mechanism \u2013 and consider their implications for the environment, in particular the reduction of aggregate emissions of pollution. We consider the cases of both complete and incomplete information.",
